1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,815
Suppose you use an AI system to grade essays, rank job
applications, review code, or choose the best answer from
several models.

2
00:00:07,815 --> 00:00:10,657
The dangerous question is: “Is the judge fair?”

3
00:00:10,657 --> 00:00:16,696
That question is too big. It invites a vague answer, and
vague answers are where bias hides.

4
00:00:16,696 --> 00:00:25,222
A better question is smaller and testable: if the same
work appears under a different irrelevant label, does the
AI judge change its score?

5
00:00:25,222 --> 00:00:35,169
In a previous video, I explained a controlled AI Village
study where the same answer was shown under different
displayed author labels. Some judges changed. One did not.

6
00:00:35,169 --> 00:00:43,339
The point was not that every AI judge plays favorites in
the same way. The point was that label effects can be
measured.

7
00:00:43,339 --> 00:00:50,089
This video is the practical version: a five-step audit you
can run before you trust an AI judge.

8
00:00:50,089 --> 00:00:54,707
Step one is to write down the decision the judge is
helping with.

9
00:00:54,707 --> 00:00:58,259
Not a generic goal like “evaluate quality.” A concrete
decision.

10
00:00:58,259 --> 00:01:07,496
For example: “Choose the strongest customer-support
answer.” Or: “Score whether this code patch follows the
requested constraints.” Or: “Rank grant proposals for
clarity and feasibility.”

11
00:01:07,496 --> 00:01:12,114
Then write down what information should matter and what
information should not matter.

12
00:01:12,114 --> 00:01:18,153
The answer text might matter. The rubric might matter.
Evidence, correctness, safety, and constraint-following
might matter.

13
00:01:18,153 --> 00:01:25,613
But the model name, applicant name, team name, vendor
name, or previous reputation might not matter for this
specific scoring task.

14
00:01:25,613 --> 00:01:32,007
That boundary is the audit target. If a label should not
matter, you can test whether it does.

15
00:01:32,007 --> 00:01:34,849
Step two is to make the rubric boring.

16
00:01:34,849 --> 00:01:42,309
A good audit rubric is not poetic. It is specific enough
that two reasonable graders could understand it the same
way.

17
00:01:42,309 --> 00:01:48,348
Use a small number of dimensions. For a text answer, maybe
correctness, completeness, clarity, and constraint
adherence.

18
00:01:48,348 --> 00:01:55,808
For a code review, maybe functional correctness,
minimality, test coverage, and risk. For a proposal, maybe
evidence, feasibility, specificity, and relevance.

19
00:01:55,808 --> 00:02:03,268
Use a fixed scale. One to five is often enough. One to ten
is fine if you really need more resolution.

20
00:02:03,268 --> 00:02:13,215
Most importantly, define the endpoints. A score of one
means what? A score of five means what? If you cannot say,
the model will invent its own scale.

21
00:02:13,215 --> 00:02:21,030
The boring rubric is not just paperwork. It reduces the
space where a judge can smuggle in a feeling about a
label.

22
00:02:21,030 --> 00:02:24,583
Step three is the heart of the audit: create pairs.

23
00:02:24,583 --> 00:02:32,043
Take the exact same item and show it to the judge twice,
but change only the label you want to test.

24
00:02:32,043 --> 00:02:39,147
Same essay, different applicant name. Same answer,
different model name. Same patch, different team label.
Same proposal, different institution label.

25
00:02:39,147 --> 00:02:45,187
If the label is irrelevant, the score should stay the same
or move only by ordinary noise.

26
00:02:45,187 --> 00:02:54,778
Keep the pair far enough apart that the judge does not
simply notice the duplicate and refuse to score it.
Shuffle the order. Mix in normal examples.

27
00:02:54,778 --> 00:02:57,975
Do not tell the judge which items are paired.

28
00:02:57,975 --> 00:03:06,856
For a quick audit, ten to twenty paired items can already
be revealing. For a higher-stakes system, use more, and
repeat across prompt types.

29
00:03:06,856 --> 00:03:16,803
The key is discipline: change one thing at a time. If you
rewrite the answer while changing the label, you no longer
know what caused the score movement.

30
00:03:16,803 --> 00:03:20,710
Step four is to score blind, then compare the paired
differences.

31
00:03:20,710 --> 00:03:28,881
Do not start with the average score for each group.
Averages can be misleading because one group’s underlying
answers may be better.

32
00:03:28,881 --> 00:03:32,078
Score with label A, minus score with label B.

33
00:03:32,078 --> 00:03:42,735
If the same item gets a higher score when labeled “trusted
vendor,” that pair has a positive trusted-label effect. If
it gets a lower score, the effect is negative.

34
00:03:42,735 --> 00:03:45,577
If it is identical, the effect is zero.

35
00:03:45,577 --> 00:03:51,972
Then summarize the paired differences. Look at the mean.
Look at how many differences point the same way.

36
00:03:51,972 --> 00:03:57,300
Look at whether effects are concentrated on weak items,
ambiguous items, or specific rubric dimensions.

37
00:03:57,300 --> 00:04:04,405
This is where a label-swap audit earns its keep. It does
not just ask whether one group scored higher.

38
00:04:04,405 --> 00:04:09,734
It asks whether the label itself moved the score while the
underlying work stayed fixed.

39
00:04:09,734 --> 00:04:12,931
Step five is to act on what you find.

40
00:04:12,931 --> 00:04:17,549
If label effects are near zero, do not declare the judge
permanently fair.

41
00:04:17,549 --> 00:04:24,654
Say something narrower: in this audit, for these labels,
on these examples, we did not find a meaningful label
effect.

42
00:04:24,654 --> 00:04:31,048
If label effects are large or one-directional, do not just
average them away. Change the evaluation process.

43
00:04:31,048 --> 00:04:40,284
Hide irrelevant labels by default. Use neutral IDs.
Separate content review from identity review. Run multiple
judges. Keep human review for borderline or high-impact
cases.

44
00:04:40,284 --> 00:04:43,837
Re-audit when the model, prompt, rubric, or domain
changes.

45
00:04:43,837 --> 00:04:50,586
And if you discover a floor-raising pattern, where a
favorable label mostly helps weaker work, pay special
attention.

46
00:04:50,586 --> 00:04:58,401
That pattern can be hard to see in average scores, but it
matters when the system is deciding which borderline
outputs pass.

47
00:04:58,401 --> 00:05:04,796
The goal is not to shame the model. The goal is to make
the decision process less fragile.

48
00:05:04,796 --> 00:05:07,638
Here is the whole audit in spreadsheet form.

49
00:05:07,638 --> 00:05:09,059
Column one: item ID.

50
00:05:09,059 --> 00:05:10,480
Column two: original text.

51
00:05:10,480 --> 00:05:13,677
Column three: label condition, such as A or B.

52
00:05:13,677 --> 00:05:15,098
Column four: judge score.

53
00:05:15,098 --> 00:05:16,874
Column five: paired item ID.

54
00:05:16,874 --> 00:05:18,295
Column six: paired difference.

55
00:05:18,295 --> 00:05:25,755
Then add a small summary: average paired difference,
number of positive differences, number of negative
differences, and notes by rubric dimension.

56
00:05:25,755 --> 00:05:29,663
That is enough to turn a vague fairness concern into
evidence.

57
00:05:29,663 --> 00:05:40,320
You do not need a giant benchmark to begin. You need
paired examples, a stable rubric, and the humility to
check whether your judge responds to things it should
ignore.

58
00:05:40,320 --> 00:05:44,227
A label-swap audit is useful, but it is not magic.

59
00:05:44,227 --> 00:05:54,174
It only tests the labels you swap. It only covers the
examples you include. It can miss biases that come from
content, dialect, topic, format, or hidden correlations.

60
00:05:54,174 --> 00:05:59,147
It can also be noisy if the judge is inconsistent from run
to run.

61
00:05:59,147 --> 00:06:03,055
So treat it as one diagnostic, not a certificate of
fairness.

62
00:06:03,055 --> 00:06:10,870
Still, it is a powerful diagnostic because it asks a
causal question in a simple way: same work, different
label, different score?

63
00:06:10,870 --> 00:06:15,133
That is much better than arguing about whether the judge
“seems objective.”

64
00:06:15,133 --> 00:06:18,686
If you use AI judges, the practical rule is simple.

65
00:06:18,686 --> 00:06:28,277
Make the irrelevant invisible. Test whether invisible
would have mattered. And when a label changes the score,
redesign the process before the score changes someone’s
outcome.

66
00:06:28,277 --> 00:06:35,382
A small audit will not solve every evaluation problem. But
it can catch a failure mode that ordinary dashboards hide.

67
00:06:35,382 --> 00:06:40,000
Same work. Different label. Different score. That is the
signal to look for.
